Challenge: Use the Nhanes data to assess if the risk of high blood lead contrations differs among ethic groups

Â 

There is no safe level of lead in the blood. Exposure to lead is particularly dangerous for children. Even trace amounts of lead in blood have been shown to damage brain cells and cause problems in mental development of children, including negative effects on IQ, ability to pay attention, and academic achievement. Moreover, these effects of lead exposure cannot be corrected . Unfortunately, lead can enter a childâ€™s environment in many ways. For example, in the USA lead-based paints were banned in 1978, but many older houses still may contain lead-based paint, especially in poorer neighborhoods where leaded paint often has not been systematically removed from old buildings houses. Water pipes may contain lead, again especially in older houses and in poorer neighborhoods, and some toys also contain lead. Living near airports or certain industries may also lead to exposure to lead in air and soil (shorturl.at/glpuL).

In the USA, risks to exposure to environmental toxicants such as lead are much higher for lower-income groups. A recent study (Yeter et al.Â 2020) based on the Nhanes survey data of the CDC showed that African-American children have by far the highest prevalence of elevated blood lead levels in the United States, after accounting for other potential factors such as household income, the presence of smokers in the home and the quality of housing. In other words, within lower-income group, the risk to be exposed to elevated lead levels in the environment during childhood is much higher for African Americans. This highlights how social economic and racial inequality drive environmental injustice.

Nhanes data used to show that African-american children have a disproportional risk of elevated blood lead levels. sources: shorturl.at/lR128 and shorturl.at/dlxJU

Â 

In this assignment, we use data from Nhanes to see if we can find similar results as the study of Yeter et al. (2020), i.e., higher blood lead levels in African-American children from lower-income households, as compared to children from other ethic groups.

Step 1: Create a new data frame lead

  • from which all rows with no blood lead data (lead_conc) are removed,
  • that only contains participants who are either non-hispanic whites or non-hispanic blacks (column ethn),
  • that only includes kids who are 6 to 10 years old (the 2018 data does not include lead concentrations for kids younger than 5 years),
  • that only contains participants on or below poverty level (poverty <= 2).
non_hisp_white_or_black <- (nhanes$ethn == "Non-Hispanic White" |
                              nhanes$ethn == "Non-Hispanic Black")

lead <- nhanes[which(!is.na(nhanes$lead_conc) &
                       non_hisp_white_or_black & 
                       nhanes$age_yrs > 5 &
                       nhanes$age_yrs < 11 &
                       nhanes$poverty <= 2) , ]

Check if you now indeed have only the two selected ethnic groups and no NAs in your lead_conc column (using code!)

unique(lead$ethn)
## [1] "Non-Hispanic Black" "Non-Hispanic White"
any(is.na(lead$lead_conc))
## [1] FALSE

Use table() to get the number of participants in each of the two ethic groups, per survey year

table(lead$ethn, lead$year)

##                      2000 2018
##   Non-Hispanic Black  135  101
##   Non-Hispanic White   56  106

Step 2: Examine graphically if the distribution of blood lead levels is normal?

Is the distribution of blood lead levels across the selected participants (low-income non-hispanic blacks and non-hispanic whites) normal? Use a histogram and QQ plot to answer the question. Plot both graphs side-to-side in a single graphical display.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

# First panel
hist(lead$lead_conc)

# Second panel
qqnorm(lead$lead_conc)
qqline(lead$lead_conc, col = "red")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
There is one very strong outlier with a value of > 2.5 umol/L. This value would indicate a very severe level of lead poisoning (https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003360.htm). Letâ€™s remove the outlier. However, we donâ€™t have sufficient information to be able to judge whether this is a correct value or was a measurement error. Therefore the correct course of action is to make a decision, analyse the data and then re-analyze the data with the outlier included in case you decided to remove it in the previous step, or the other way around. You would use this second analysis to assess how strongly your conclusions are effected by your decision to keep/remove the outlier.

Step 7: Assess if lead levels differ among ethnic groups

Does the mean blood lead levels differ among non-hispanic whites and non-hispanic blacks? Look at this for the years 2000 and 2018 separately.

aggregate(lead_conc ~ ethn, data = lead[lead$year == 2000,], FUN = mean)
##                 ethn lead_conc
## 1 Non-Hispanic Black 0.1214925
## 2 Non-Hispanic White 0.0986250
aggregate(lead_conc ~ ethn, data = lead[lead$year == 2018,], FUN = mean)
##                 ethn  lead_conc
## 1 Non-Hispanic Black 0.03207921
## 2 Non-Hispanic White 0.03735849
Just eyeballing the data, in 2000 the mean blood lead level of non-hispanic black participants was considerably higher then that of non-hispanic white participants. In 2018, means of the two ethic groups were very similar. Interestingly, mean blood lead levels more than halved over the 2000-2018 period. However, remember that the data was strongly skewed, so is the mean actually the best way of comparing the groups?

Â 

Step 8: Letâ€™s do the same but now calculate the medians.

aggregate(lead_conc ~ ethn, data = lead[lead$year == 2000,], FUN = median)
##                 ethn lead_conc

## 2 Non-Hispanic White     0.070
aggregate(lead_conc ~ ethn, data = lead[lead$year == 2018,], FUN = median)
##                 ethn lead_conc
## 1 Non-Hispanic Black      0.03
## 2 Non-Hispanic White      0.03
The differences in medians suggest higher lead levels in N-h blacks in 2000 but no difference in 2018. There is also a substantial decrease in median lead levels from 2000 to 2018.

Step 9: Use boxplots to compare groups

Now plot the data in box plots. Add appropriate x-axis and y-axis labels. Give the survey year as graph title. Use the names = argument to define the x-axis labels. Plot the two box plots side-to-side together in one graphical display.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))

boxplot(lead_conc ~ ethn,
        data = lead[lead$year == 2000, ],
        ylim = c(0, max(lead$lead_conc)),
        main = "2000",
        xlab = "ethic group",
        ylab = "blood lead concentration",
        names = c("N.-h. black", "N.-h. white"),
        col = "coral1")
grid()
boxplot(lead_conc ~ ethn,
        data = lead[lead$year == 2018, ],
        ylim = c(0, max(lead$lead_conc)),
        main = "2018",
        xlab = "ethic group",
        ylab = "blood lead concentration",
        names = c("N.-h. black", "N.-h. white"),
        col = "cyan3")
grid()

par(mfrow = c(1,1))

The box plots show that the median blood lead concentration of 6-10 year old N-h black participants was higher than that of N-h white participants in 2000 and that this difference disappeared in 2018 (as we calculated before). Not only did the median blood lead concentrations decreased substantially, also the variation in blood lead concentrations among the participants decreased a lot.

Perhaps the average of blood lead levels is not the best metric for comparing the risk of exposure to lead between two groups. What may matter more is the proportion of children in each group that have blood lead levels above a certain threshold. The USA Centers for Disease Control and Prevention ( CDC, they are responsible for the annual Nhanes surveys) currently uses a blood lead reference value of 0.24 Âµmol/L to identify children who have been exposed to lead and who require further testing and monitoring. Please see their website for more information (shorturl.at/oAQ48). Letâ€™s therefore compare the proportion of children in both ethic groups with lead levels above the 0.24 Âµmol/L threshold.

Subset the dataframe lead to create a new data frame lead_high with only those children that had a blood lead concentration of 0.24 or higher.

lead_high <- lead[lead$lead_conc >= 0.24,]
